:"1400–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1350–Male":"1350–Overleden","1355–Female":"1355–Overleden","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, England","Loddon, Norfolk, England":"Loddon, Norfolk, England","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1375–1413":"1375–1413","–Female":"Deceased","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1355–Female":"1355–Deceased","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, England","Loddon, Norfolk, England":"Loddon, Norfolk, England","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hales","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (widespread, especially in the southeast): from the genitive singular or nominative plural form of Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’ (see   Hale  ).","Irish: when not of English origin, this may be a variant of   Healy   or   McHale  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hale","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived in a (usually remote) nook or corner of land, from Old English and Middle English <i>hale</i>, dative of <i>h(e)alh</i> ‘nook, hollow’, or a habitational name from a place so named such as Hale in Cheshire, Hampshire, Lancashire, Lincolnshire, Holme Hale (Norfolk), Hale Street (Kent), and Haile (Cumberland). In northern England the word often has a specialized meaning, denoting a piece of flat alluvial land by the side of a river, typically one deposited in a bend. See   Haugh  . In southeastern England it often referred to a patch of dry land in a fen. In some cases the surname may be a habitational name from any of several places in England named with this fossilized inflected form, which would originally have been preceded by a preposition, e.g. <i>in the hale</i> or <i>at the hale</i>. This surname is also established in south Wales.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Céile</b> (see   McHale  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Halle  ."]},{"name":"Hayles","meanings":["English:","variant of   Hales  .","variant of   Ayles   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Hailes","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Hailes in Colinton (Midlothian), originally in East Lothian, named from the Middle English genitive or plural form of <i>hall</i> ‘hall’.","English: variant of   Hales   (see also   Hayles  )."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Coroner Roger de Hales was born in 1375, in Hales, Norfolk, England, his father, Ranulphus de Hales, was 25 and his mother, Dameta Clevor, was 20. He married miss Scogan in 1399, in Hales, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1413, in Loddon, Norfolk, England, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1375–1413":"1375–1413","–Female":"Surnud","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, England","Loddon, Norfolk, England":"Loddon, Norfolk, England","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1375–1413":"1375–1413","–Female":"Kuollut","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, England","Loddon, Norfolk, England":"Loddon, Norfolk, England","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, England"},"fr":{"1375–1413":"1375–1413","–Female":"Décédée","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1355–Female":"1355–Décédée","1413":"1413","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1374":"1374","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Hales, Norfolk, England":"Hales, Norfolk, Angleterre","Loddon, Norfolk, England":"Loddon, Norfolk, Angleterre","Wood Norton, Norfolk, England":"Wood Norton, Norfolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Coroner Roger de Hales est né en 1375, à Hales, Norfolk, Angleterre, son père, Ranulphus de 